eir deepest fears and prejudices. The diverse experiences and changing beliefs of Blauner's interview subjects—sixteen of them Black, twelve of them white—are expanded through subsequent interviews in 1979 and 1986, revealing as much about ordinary, daily lives as the extraordinary cultural shifts that shaped them. This book remains a landmark historical and sociological document, and an exceptional primary-source commentary on the development of race relations since the 1960s. Republished with a foreword by Professor Gerald Early, Black Lives, White Lives offers new generations of scholars and activists a galvanizing meditation on how divided America was then and still is today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aInterviewszUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1968.  a1979.  a1986.  a20th century.  aafrican americans.  aamerica.  aamerican history.  aanthropology.  ablack americans.  ablack experience.  ablack life.  aclass differences.  acontemporary issues.  aethnic demographic studies.  akkk.  amen and women.  anaacp.  anonfiction.  apersonal dramas.  apersonal interviews.  apolitical change.  apolitical issues.  arace relations.  aracial change.  aracial consciousness.  aracial issues.  aracial prejudice.  aracial tensions.  aracism.  asocial change.  asocial commentary.  asocial history.  asociology.  awhite americans.  awhiteness.1 aAdams, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbert, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooke, Vera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/